From 28fa72ca43bb05ce7e9af91f632af6c7cb624b90 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Rudi Heitbaum <rudi@heitbaum.com>
Date: Fri, 24 Apr 2026 09:41:06 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] target: add LibreELEC target specifications for aarch64,
 armv7a, armv7ve, and x86_64
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Add four new Rust target specifications for LibreELEC. These targets
replace the previous JSON-based custom target definitions in the LibreELEC
build system.

Targets added:
  - aarch64-libreelec-linux-gnu
  - armv7a-libreelec-linux-gnueabihf
  - armv7ve-libreelec-linux-gnueabihf
  - x86_64-libreelec-linux-gnu

Each target is based on its corresponding upstream Linux GNU target
(aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu, arm-unknown-linux-gnueabihf, x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu)
and inherits all defaults from base::linux_gnu::opts(), with the following
LibreELEC-specific overrides applied:

aarch64-libreelec-linux-gnu:
  - supported_sanitizers: ADDRESS | CFI | LEAK | MEMORY | MEMTAG | THREAD | HWADDRESS
    Drops KCFI and REALTIME. Retains MEMTAG and HWADDRESS which provide
    valuable memory safety tooling on AArch64 hardware.
  - supports_xray: false (upstream: true)

armv7a-libreelec-linux-gnueabihf:
armv7ve-libreelec-linux-gnueabihf:
  - features: +strict-align,+v6,+vfp2,-d32
    Adds -d32 to the upstream feature set to disable the upper 16
    double-precision VFP registers. Targets older ARM SoCs common in
    LibreELEC-supported media devices (Amlogic, Rockchip, Allwinner)
    whose VFP units provide only 16 double-precision registers.
  - No sanitizer overrides; upstream arm-unknown-linux-gnueabihf defines
    none and the LibreELEC JSON spec lists none.

x86_64-libreelec-linux-gnu:
  - stack_probes: Call (upstream: Inline)
    Conservative stack probing via function call rather than inlined
    instructions. Reduces code size on appliance hardware where probe
    performance is not a concern.
  - supported_sanitizers: ADDRESS | CFI | LEAK | MEMORY | THREAD
    Drops KCFI, DATAFLOW, SAFESTACK, and REALTIME which require toolchain
    support not present in LibreELEC builds.
  - supports_xray: false (upstream: true)

All four targets are registered in supported_targets! in
compiler/rustc_target/src/spec/mod.rs.

Metadata:
  - tier: 3 (community-maintained, not part of official Rust CI)
  - host_tools: false (LibreELEC is a read-only appliance OS)
  - std: true

